the election of the new President, Enrique Peña Nieto and the changes he has introduced. I’m not looking at the pros and cons of the new attitude and politics of coverage per se or even the Internet per se. In fact I’m not looking at that at all. Many people have spoken at length about that and I think it’s time we all looked at a bigger picture. What has the new President done for Mexican telcos?

Poor Q4 results

The first thing we need to examine is that most of Mexico’s telcos have had a very poor Q4. Today, Iberdrola’s CEO conceded that the company did not make money in Q4. At least not the traditional scheme of making money: connecting a customer, billing him for 3 months, collecting the money.

Giving out free phone plans

Back in ’96, adjusted for inflation, I paid roughly 600-700 pesos. Today that you would pay roughly US$90 for a plan. The funny part is that the 3 key elements that make up a telecom base plan haven’t changed that much: free minutes, text messages and data. Even calls to landline have not considerably increased.

Believe it or not, unbundling the fixed base offered, the actual services I have:
